ewspaper reports of the royal family intensified in intimacy and its members became moral exemplars-most often, paradoxically, when they misbehaved. Ad hominem attacks on political leaders became commonplace; politicians of all affiliations continued to assess one another's characters based on their success and daring with women and money. And newly popular human-interest journalism promoted the illusion that the personal characters of public figures could be read by appearances.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aJournalismxPolitical aspectszEnglandxHistory. 0aPress and politicszGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook Package 2014-2015z978311067250308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook Package 2014-2016z978311053800708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300210477423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300210477.jpg  a978-3-11-053800-7  YUP eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-067250-3  YUP eBook Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles